{"type":"message","id":"a380887d","parentId":"8d8110e5","timestamp":"2026-02-17T19:27:43.907Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"exec_1771356463476_125","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Generating 10k storm strings...\r\nStarting sanitization loop...\r\nProcessed 10000 items in 0.0110s\r\nLatency: 0.0011 ms/op\r\n\r\nSUCCESS: No injections passed sanitization."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":424,"aggregated":"Generating 10k storm strings...\r\nStarting sanitization loop...\r\nProcessed 10000 items in 0.0110s\r\nLatency: 0.0011 ms/op\r\n\r\nSUCCESS: No injections passed sanitization.","cwd":"C:\\Users\\west2\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1771356463905}}
{"type":"message","id":"f6042bcd","parentId":"a380887d","timestamp":"2026-02-17T19:28:08.615Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Reviewing the Stress Test**\n\nI've checked the source code for `src/stress_test_shm.py`. It looks like it could work, but I need to confirm it handles the shared memory aspects I'm looking for. I'm taking a closer look at the worker configuration now to make sure it matches my expectations for the load.\n\n\n**Initiating Code Inspection**\n\nI'm now in the process of thoroughly reviewing `src/stress_test_shm.py`. My primary concern is verifying that the script can effectively simulate the desired memory overload scenario, specifically focusing on the number of workers and the interval between their operations. If it doesn't align perfectly, I'll either adapt it or develop a new script to fulfill the requirements.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771356488494_126","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"src/stress_test_shm.py"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":115741,"output":120,"cacheRead":114665,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":115861,"cost":{"input":0.231482,"output":0.00144,"cacheRead":0.022933000000000002,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.255855}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771356463908}}
{"type":"message","id":"ce32405b","parentId":"f6042bcd","timestamp":"2026-02-17T19:28:08.645Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771356488494_126","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\nimport time\nimport multiprocessing\nfrom multiprocessing import shared_memory\nimport struct\n\ndef stress_test_shm():\n    # 4 floats (CS2, Rust, TF2, Dota) = 4 * 8 bytes (double) = 32 bytes\n    # actually ShareableList handles types, but for raw speed usually struct is better?\n    # The prompt asks for ShareableList explicitly: \"Use multiprocessing.shared_memory.ShareableList\"\n    \n    data = [0.0, 0.0, 0.0, 0.0]\n    shm_name = \"stress_test_shm\"\n    \n    try:\n        sl = shared_memory.ShareableList(data, name=shm_name)\n    except FileExistsError:\n        # Cleanup if exists from previous run\n        existing = shared_memory.ShareableList(name=shm_name)\n        existing.shm.unlink()\n        sl = shared_memory.ShareableList(data, name=shm_name)\n\n    iterations = 100000\n    start_write = time.perf_counter()\n    for i in range(iterations):\n        sl[0] = float(i)\n        sl[1] = float(i)\n        sl[2] = float(i)\n        sl[3] = float(i)\n    end_write = time.perf_counter()\n    \n    start_read = time.perf_counter()\n    for i in range(iterations):\n        _ = sl[0]\n        _ = sl[1]\n        _ = sl[2]\n        _ = sl[3]\n    end_read = time.perf_counter()\n    \n    avg_write = ((end_write - start_write) / iterations) * 1000 # ms\n    avg_read = ((end_read - start_read) / iterations) * 1000 # ms\n    \n    print(f\"Write Latency: {avg_write:.5f} ms\")\n    print(f\"Read Latency: {avg_read:.5f} ms\")\n    \n    sl.shm.close()\n    sl.shm.unlink()\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    stress_test_shm()\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771356488641}}
{"type":"message","id":"a2d3330b","parentId":"ce32405b","timestamp":"2026-02-17T19:28:28.700Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Refactoring the Test Script**\n\nI'm now focused on rewriting the `stress_test_shm.py` script. The goal is to simulate four workers writing to shared memory with a 50ms interval, to test the ResourceTracker and CPU usage. The current single-worker sequential approach is insufficient. My next step involves defining the worker behavior and introducing concurrency.\n\n\n**Developing Worker Processes**\n\nI've sketched out the initial steps for the new `memory_overload.py` script. It will spawn four worker processes, each interacting with shared memory, as the requirements specify. I'm thinking of using `multiprocessing.shared_memory.SharedMemory` for data exchange between the processes. Next, I need to implement the 50ms sleep interval within each worker and define the overall test duration to monitor for warnings and CPU spikes.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771356508699_127","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"import time\nimport multiprocessing\nfrom multiprocessing import shared_memory, Process\nimport random\nimport os\nimport sys\n\ndef worker_task(worker_id, shm_name, duration=5):\n    \"\"\"\n    Worker writes to its assigned slot in shared memory every 50ms.\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        # Attach to existing SHM\n        sl = shared_memory.ShareableList(name=shm_name)\n        \n        print(f\"Worker {worker_id} started (pid: {os.getpid()})\")\n        start_time = time.time()\n        writes = 0\n        \n        while time.time() - start_time < duration:\n            # Write random float to our slot\n            val = random.random() * 1000\n            sl[worker_id] = val\n            writes += 1\n            time.sleep(0.05)  # 50ms interval\n            \n        print(f\"Worker {worker_id} finished. Writes: {writes}\")\n        sl.shm.close()\n        \n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"Worker {worker_id} crashed: {e}\")\n\ndef run_memory_overload():\n    num_workers = 4\n    duration = 10 # run for 10 seconds\n    \n    # Initialize shared memory for 4 floats\n    # Slot 0: Worker 1, Slot 1: Worker 2, etc.\n    init_data = [0.0] * num_workers\n    shm_name = \"memory_overload_shm\"\n    \n    # Clean up if exists\n    try:\n        existing = shared_memory.ShareableList(name=shm_name)\n        existing.shm.unlink()\n        print(f\"Cleaned up stale SHM: {shm_name}\")\n    except FileNotFoundError:\n        pass\n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"Warning during cleanup: {e}\")\n\n    # Create new SHM\n    sl = shared_memory.ShareableList(init_data, name=shm_name)\n    print(f\"Shared Memory '{shm_name}' created. Size: {len(sl)} slots.\")\n\n    processes = []\n    \n    try:\n        # Spawn workers\n        for i in range(num_workers):\n            p = Process(target=worker_task, args=(i, shm_name, duration))\n            processes.append(p)\n            p.start()\n            \n        # Monitor loop\n        start_monitor = time.time()\n        while time.time() - start_monitor < duration:\n            # Main process reads all slots occasionally to simulate consumer\n            current_vals = [sl[i] for i in range(num_workers)]\n            # print(f\"Monitor: {current_vals}\") # too noisy\n            time.sleep(1)\n            \n        # Join workers\n        for p in processes:\n            p.join()\n            \n    finally:\n        # Cleanup\n        print(\"Cleaning up SHM...\")\n        sl.shm.close()\n        sl.shm.unlink()\n        print(\"Memory Overload Test Complete.\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    run_memory_overload()\n","file_path":"scripts/memory_overload.py"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":116441,"output":938,"cacheRead":114693,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":117379,"cost":{"input":0.23288199